{"id":"2206.03940","submitter":"Pavel Rodin","authors":"Aleksander Rozkhov, Mikhail Ivanov, Pavel Rodin","title":"The lock-on effect and collapsing bipolar Gunn domains in high-voltage\n  GaAs avalanche p-n junction diode","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present experimental evidence and physics-based simulations of the lock-on\neffect in high-voltage GaAs avalanche diodes. The avalanche triggering is\ninitiated by steep voltage ramp applied to the diode and in-series 50 Ohm load.\nAfter subnanosecond avalanche switching the reversely biased GaAs diode remains\nin the conducting state for the whole duration of the applied pulse (dozens of\nnanoseconds). There is no indication of the p-n junction recovery that is\ncommonly expected to develop on the nanosecond scale due to the drift\nextraction of non-equilibrium carriers. The diode voltage keeps a constant\nvalue of ~70 V much lower than the stationary breakdown voltage of 400 V.\nNumerical simulations reveal that the conducting state is supported by impact\nionization in narrow high-field collapsing Gunn domains as well as in\nquasi-stationary cathode and anode ionizing domains. Collapsing Gunn domains\nspontaneously appear in the dense electron-hole plasma due to the negative\ndifferential mobility of electrons in GaAs. The effect resembles the lock-on\neffect of GaAs bulk photoconductive switches but is observed in reversely\nbiased p-n junction diode switched by a non-optical method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Jun 2022 15:00:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 13 Jun 2022 20:49:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-15"}
